✅ Set A: System Administration & Maintenance
🔹 1) Timestamped Backup Script
#!/bin/bash

SOURCE="/home/user/data"
DESTINATION="/backup"
DATE=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")

mkdir -p $DESTINATION/$DATE
cp -r $SOURCE $DESTINATION/$DATE

echo "Backup completed successfully on $DATE"
✔ Explanation:
SOURCE → folder to backup
DESTINATION → where backup is stored
DATE → creates unique folder (prevents overwrite)
mkdir -p → creates directory safely
cp -r → copies all files recursively
echo → success message
🔹 2) Disk Usage Monitor Script
#!/bin/bash

THRESHOLD=80

df -H | grep -vE '^Filesystem|tmpfs|cdrom' | awk '{print $5 " " $1}' | while read output;
do
    usage=$(echo $output | awk '{print $1}' | cut -d'%' -f1)
    partition=$(echo $output | awk '{print $2}')

    if [ $usage -ge $THRESHOLD ]; then
        echo "⚠ Warning: Disk usage on $partition is at ${usage}%"
    fi
done
✔ Explanation:
df -H → disk usage
grep -vE → removes unwanted lines
awk → extracts columns
while read → loop through each partition
cut → removes %
condition checks if usage ≥ 80%
🔹 3) Jenkins Service Watchdog
#!/bin/bash

SERVICE="jenkins"

if systemctl is-active --quiet $SERVICE
then
    echo "$SERVICE is running"
else
    echo "$SERVICE is not running. Starting service..."
    systemctl start $SERVICE

    if systemctl is-active --quiet $SERVICE
    then
        echo "$SERVICE started successfully"
    else
        echo "Failed to start $SERVICE"
    fi
fi
✔ Explanation:
systemctl is-active --quiet → checks service silently
systemctl start → starts service
nested if → confirms restart
✅ Set B: Networking & Logging
🔹 4) Host Reachability Script
#!/bin/bash

HOST="google.com"
OUTPUT_FILE="ping_results.log"

if ping -c 1 $HOST &> /dev/null
then
    echo "$(date): $HOST is reachable" >> $OUTPUT_FILE
else
    echo "$(date): $HOST is not reachable" >> $OUTPUT_FILE
fi
✔ Explanation:
ping -c 1 → send 1 packet
&> /dev/null → hide output
>> → append log
date → adds timestamp
🔹 5) Database Backup Script
#!/bin/bash

DB_NAME="school"
BACKUP_DIR="/backups"
DATE=$(date +"%Y-%m-%d_%H-%M-%S")

mkdir -p $BACKUP_DIR

echo "Enter MySQL password:"
read -s PASSWORD

mysqldump -u root -p$PASSWORD $DB_NAME > $BACKUP_DIR/$DB_NAME-$DATE.sql

echo "Database backup completed: $BACKUP_DIR/$DB_NAME-$DATE.sql"
✔ Explanation:
read -s → hides password input
mysqldump → exports database
file saved with timestamp
